==Old English==
===Etymology===
Via Germanic, from Indo-European ''*newn-'' ‘nine’.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[nigun]] (Frisian [[njoggen]]), Old Saxon [[nigun]] (Dutch [[negen]]), together representing a variant of the original Germanic (with /g/ for /w/), seen in Old High German [[niun]] (German [[neun]]), Old Norse ''níu'' (Swedish [[nio]]), Gothic [[𐌽𐌹𐌿𐌽]].  The IE source also led to Latin [[novem]], Old Irish ''nōi'' (Irish [[naoi]]), Old Slavic ''devęt’'' (Russian [[девять]]).

